{"question": "Let $f(x)$ be an odd function, and let $g(x)$ be an even function.  Is $f(f(g(f(g(f(x))))))$ even, odd, or neither?\n\nEnter \"odd\", \"even\", or \"neither\".", "groundtruth": "We have that\n\\[f(f(g(f(g(f(-x)))))) = f(f(g(f(g(-f(x)))))) = f(f(g(f(g(f(x)))))),\\]so the function is $\\boxed{\\text{even}}.$\n\nMore generally, if we have a composition of functions, and at least one of the functions is even, then the whole composition of functions is even.", "result": {"majority_vote": 0, "total_completion_tokens": 8112}, "output": [{"path_idx": 0, "text": "To determine whether \\( f(f(g(f(g(f(x)))))) \\) is even, odd, or neither, we need to analyze the properties of the functions \\( f \\) and \\( g \\) and how they interact when composing. ки\n### Step 1: Properties of \\( f \\) and \\( g \\)\n- \\( f(x) \\) is an **odd function**.\n  - This means \\( f(-x) = -f(x) \\) for all \\( x \\).\n- \\( g(x) \\) is an **even function**.\n  - This means \\( g(-x) = g(x) \\) for all \\( x \\). ки\n### Step 2: Compose \\( f \\) and \\( g \\) in a specific manner\nWe need to analyze the expression \\( f(f(g(f(g(f(x)))))) \\). ки\n### Step 3: Compute \\( f(g(f(g(f(x))))) \\)\nLet's denote \\( y = f(x) \\). Then we need to compute:\n  \\[\n  f(g(y)) = f(g(f(x)))\n  \\]\n  Using the even property of \\( g \\), we get:\n  \\[\n  f(g(y)) = f(g(f(x))) = f(g(f(x)))\n  \\] ки\n### Step 4: Compute \\( f(g(f(g(f(x))))) \\)\nNext, compute \\( f(g(f(g(f(x))))) \\):\n  \\[\n  f(g(f(g(f(x))))) = f(g(f(g(f(x))))) = f(g(f(g(f(x))))) = f(g(f(g(f(x))))) = f(g(f(g(f(x))))) = f(g(f(g(f(x))))) = f(g(f(g(f(x))))) = f(g(f(g(f(x))))) = f(g(f(g(f(x))))) = f(g(f(g(f(x))))) = f(g(f(g(f(x))))) = f(g(f(g(f(x))))) = f(g(f(g(f(x))))) = f(g(f(g(f(x))))) = f(g(f(g(f(x))))) = f(g(f(g(f(x))))) = f(g(f(g(f(x))))) = f(g(f(g(f(x))))) = f(g(f(g(f(x))))) = f(g(f(g(f(x))))) = f(g(f(g(f(x))))) = f(g(f(g(f(x))))) = f(g(f(g(f(x))))) = f(g(f(g(f(x))))) = f(g(f(g(f(x))))) = f(g(f(g(f(x))))) = f(g(f(g(f(x))))) =